This analysis detects scanf-like calls whose return value is ignored.
1. Is the return value captured or checked on all paths?
2. How many items should be parsed from the format string?
3. Are destination variables used after the call without guaranteed initialization?
4. Is the input source trusted or attacker-controlled?
Use the tools to confirm whether parse failure can propagate into unsafe behavior.
If the return value is effectively checked or failures are safely handled, there is no issue.
Only flag if unchecked parse failures can lead to incorrect logic or memory misuse.
